First is the image of the &amp;#34;fierce savage&amp;#34; - Current legal framing and stereotypes of enforce two equally dangerous representations, the first of which is the &amp;#34;fierce savage&amp;#34; who owns casinos and plays fast and loose with the law – these images pre-frame decision making vis-à-vis American Indians.

Tsosie 10
(Rebecca – (Yaqui) Sandra Day O’Conner College of Law, Arizona State University; &amp;#34;Indians %26 Energy&amp;#34;; ed Sherry L. Smith and Brian Frehner; School for Advanced Research Press. P. 263-4)

Speaking at a conference on cultural sovereignty at the Arizona State¶ University College of 
AND
develop will¶ determine our collective destiny on the lands that sustain us.


Second is the &amp;#34;noble savage&amp;#34; – The patronizing image of American Indians as land-loving hippies created the American Indian as the abject– the perverse underside of the sophisticated, urbane American identity that needed to be repressed and eliminated. Historical encounters with America’s abjected other have led to objectification and genocide.

Aldama 1
(Arturo J. – Prof Ethnic Studies University of Colorado Boulder; &amp;#34;Disrupting Savagism; Intersecting Chicana/o, Mexican Immigrant, and Native American Struggles for Sel-Representation&amp;#34;; Duke UP; p. 14-6)
By contrast, the Dominican bishop of Chiapas, Bartolome de Las Casas,¶ a 
AND
century (an issue¶ I discuss in greater detail in chapter 4).


The defining of an American subject in opposition to the abject &amp;#34;noble savage&amp;#34; writes more than just Indians into oppression. The constitution of the American subject has all but eliminated the Native as its perverse underside. Absent an ethical intervention, the continuing process of abjection ensures that America will only ever define the social ideal as white and male, thereby eliminating all other identities.

